this is what I usually tell people to do:<p><pre><code>  var els = document.getElementsByTagName('li');//use var unless you really really really meant global
  for(var i=0; i < els.length; i++){
    (function(i) {//creates new scope for each iteration
      els[i].addEventListener('click', function(){alert(i);}, false);
    })(i);
  }</code></pre>

Just adding var wouldn't be enough, you're still referencing the variable from the outer scope. You need to create your own copy. Instead of:<p><pre><code>    els[i].addEventListener('click', function(){alert(i);});
</code></pre>
Do:<p><pre><code>    els[i].addEventListener('click',
        function() {
            var j = i;
            alert(j);
        });
</code></pre>
